The issue is that RabbitMQ doesn't automatically propagate W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers like HTTP does. You need to manually inject context into message headers on publish and extract it on consume.

**Service A – Publisher (inject context):**

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Create an ActivitySource for your publisher
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("order.publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current trace context into message headers
if (activity != null)
{
    props.Headers["traceparent"] = activity.Id;
    props.Headers["tracestate"] = activity.Context.TraceState ?? "";
}

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

**Service B – Consumer (extract context):**

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");

// In your consumer callback:
void OnReceived(object sender, BasicDeliverEventArgs ea)
{
    // Extract propagated context from headers
    ActivityContext parentCtx = default;
    if (ea.BasicProperties.Headers?.TryGetValue("traceparent", out var raw) == true)
    {
        var traceparent = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])raw);
        ActivityContext.TryParse(traceparent, null, out parentCtx);
    }

    using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
        "order.process",
        ActivityKind.Consumer,
        parentContext: parentCtx  // ← links the trace
    );

    // Process the message — this activity now shares the same TraceId
}
```

**Wire up in `Program.cs` (both services):**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")   // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

**Why this works:** `activity.Id` is the W3C `traceparent` string (e.g., `00-<traceId>-<spanId>-01`). By passing it through RabbitMQ's header dictionary and parsing it back as the `parentContext`, Service B's spans join the same distributed trace.

**Alternatively**, if you use [MassTransit](https://masstransit.io/) or the [`RabbitMQ.Client.OpenTelemetry`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/RabbitMQ.Client.OpenTelemetry) package (v7+), this injection/extraction is done automatically — no manual header wiring needed.
